For a perfect crystal, the phonon contribution comes from the center of the Brilliouin zone satisfying the phonon momentum selection rule, q ≈ 0 (Zhang et al. 2000). In semiconductor nanoparticles, the phonon selection rule breaks and the phonon momentum distribution increases. The phonon scattering thus involves phonon contribution from the entire Brillouin zone (Brojcin et al. 2005, Mo and Ching 1995). For nanoparticles of diameter (d), the intensity for first-order Raman scattering is given by:5I(ω)=C0,k2[ω−ω(k)]2+(Γo2)2d3q\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
